column5:
i think it's a worthwhile discussion! i've read that imperial club can be a bit of a scrum but clearly not everyone's experience! certainly when they (many years ago) used the old bar azure (i think that's what it was called!) as one of the places where you could get free drinks in the early evening, it meant it was suddenly packed, which really irritated me as it used to be our favourite place for a glass of champagne before dinner, listening to the piano player and feeding our children the little vegetable stick cruditÃ©s that they handed out. so perhaps that's rather coloured my own view of ic...
but anyway... the ic lounge breakfast is advertised as 'continental' - we like saffron because, due to the time zone, we get up late, have a fairly substantial brunch, and that sees us through several hours in the waterpark. i'm personally a fan of the big vegetarian offering that they have (you can also get pork sausages and bacon if that's your thing). the dim sum is ok, there's lots of fruit, pastries, cereal - and yes even the massive chocolate fountain.
so depends what you want, but we tend to go big on breakfast and then not bother with lunch.

column4: self catering look lakelovers "heart lakes" (now jointly owned) cumbrian cottages, select ones swimming pool access, many though. hotels allow book leisure day passes swimming, avoid public swimming baths troutbeck gets busy. nowhere flat lakes cycle except old keswick railway line, hire, i'm sure advice. brockhole windermere lots activities kids, used summer classes adventure book quickly. number honister via ferrata, never forget experience. wet days (you them) kendal indoor climbing center great, drink watch child learn climb safely, ambleside well tried that, lot smaller. prefer ambleside central places, craxy golf, putting, tennis well easier walks, grasmere. someone said ambleside yha good, best place lakes sit outside drink right lake, pubs near by. platty kayaking derwent good, sure windy day though.
column5: self catering look at lakelovers and "heart of the lakes" (now jointly owned) and cumbrian cottages, you can select ones with swimming pool access, not many now though. some hotels allow you to book leisure day passes to go swimming, avoid the public swimming baths at troutbeck it gets very busy. nowhere is flat in the lakes to cycle except maybe the old keswick railway line, but ask before you hire, i'm sure they can give advice. brockhole on windermere has lots of activities for kids, they also used to do summer classes for adventure things but they book up very quickly. number one thing to do is the honister via ferrata, you will never forget the experience. for wet days (you will get them) kendal indoor climbing center is great, you can just have a drink and watch your child learn to climb safely, there is one at ambleside as well but not tried that, it is a lot smaller. we prefer ambleside as it is central for most places, it has craxy golf, putting, tennis as well and some easier walks, such as to grasmere. as someone said ambleside yha is good, best place in the lakes to sit outside and have a drink right on the lake, better than the pubs near by. platty kayaking on derwent is really good, make sure it is not a windy day though.

column5:
hi,
first to note to avoid any confusion that the kembali villas you listed in post #3 (perhaps it was an auto link) is not kembali beach bungalows in amed.
kembali villas linked in post #3 are in seminyak.
do you dive or just snorkeling.
pemuteran
check exact location of any property carefully. pemuteran spreads out a long way also inland.
pemuteran is mrs pigs favourite after amed.
we stay at 
you have to walk down the beach a little to enter the sea for snorkeling. main reasons is that their are a lot of sea urchins in the sea along with low lying reefs close to shore. there is a signpost.
entry is more or less in front of the pondok sari.
you will also find the biorock reef restoration project.
the only thing is that pemuteran bay is very sandy (just offshore). at full moon/spring tides/windy/choppy seas the sand can get churned up in the bay. even snorkeling close to shore it can be like snorkeling in a milkshake. literally canâ€™t see your hand in front of your face. biorock not visible.
iâ€™ve been diving well offshore and when in shallower water 10-15m on a sunny day it was like diving in a snowglobe with all the glistening sand.
i use the dive centre on the beach behind the swimming pool/wellness massage centre.

they have 2 dive boats. one rib and one larger fibreglass hull boat.
if only snorkeling you can enquire at the dive centre or others along the beach, about snorkeling trips menjangan.
dive trips often willing to take snorkelers if space. advantage is the boat goes from the beach.
you can arrange snorkeling trips locally but this may involve a road trip in a minibus before picking up a local boat.
out on the main singaraja road you will find a few restaurants geared up for tourists. we particularly like warung tirta sari at tirta sari bungalows opposite suka sari bungalows and warung.
also nearby selini bakery does some nice cakes.

column5:
strongly recommend the last few nights at sanur, rather than benoa.
it is very easy to connect with the charming locals and get up close and personal with some of the local culture. there are beachfront restaurants and charming small warungs, where you can sit with your feet in the sand and gaze out to sea watching the fisherman standing chest deep in the calm water, as you drink cold beer and eat fresh fish or spicy noodles.......doesn't get any better.
when you're ready for exercise, the beachfront walking path offers kilometres of sea views and bali life all around you,and the opportunity for endless stops along the way for bbq corn, icecream or a cocktail.

column5:
i went to durham to see the cathedral on tuesday, july 6, and i wanted to share my experience with other would-be travelers.
-book the guided tour in advance. it was sold out for the day i went, and i had been waiting many years to visit the cathedral (romanesque architecture is my absolute favorite). it did not even occur to me that i needed to book many days in advance. i honestly thought i would cry when they kindly said it was sold out*. i texted my children and husband; my husband offered to try to find me a private tour guide immediately, but there was not way that could have worked out. very sweet of him, though.
-tour groups are currently limited to 5 or 6 ppl total. i was confused bc there was at least 1 large school group there on that day; many more than 5-6 ppl. i realize the rules come from the uk govt, not the cathedral. i realize that the cathedral is doing its best to follow what seem to be confusing rules (a big school group = ok, +6 adults in a tour group = not ok). it is what it is--just know them before you go.
-reserve a table in the cafe if you think you might eat there, or eat after 2pm.
*i did not cry, although i may never get to go to durham again (i live in tx), because of the volunteers at the cathedral. i would especially like to highlight hazel, a docent who was so helpful. she was like an angel. she answered my many questions in great detail and was the best of the british--kind, knowledgeable, and with a reserve that comes from a deep well of very good manners. she made me feel i could ask as many questions as i wanted to.
another female docent, tall, thin, with a sporty short haircut, encouraged me to buy a guidebook (which i did) and it was so helpful. many thanks to her.
it was a miserable day--chilly and pouring rain. a chipper younger woman at the entrance pointed out the river path to the bridge, and i'm so glad she did; it was a wonderful (although chilly) walk.
i arrived on a train from london; there is a bus that runs you to the cathedral every 15 minutes or so. many thanks to the women working in the station that day who pointed me in the right direction to catch the bus.
the bus driver was so nice and friendly. such an asset to durham and i'm sorry i did not make note of his name.
i had not eaten all day and, after seeing most of the cathedral, i went down to the cafe on a chance; there was 1 unreserved table at 2:15 (the guided tour started at 2). the women working in the cafe were very helpful. i had the lasagna special (lasagna, bread, and a salad) and a giant (hot and cozy) latte. my lunch was delicious and perfect for the weather.
there was a young, young woman in the gift shop; she was precious and sweet. the shop has a very good book on the architecture of the cathedral which i have been reading.
i wandered around the immediate area before catching the bus back to the train station and back to london. 6 hours on a train; 3 hours in durham.
all of the people i have referenced were at their posts after 12:20 on july 6. they deserve recognition. if there is any way to forward my thanks to them, please let me know.
the cathedral is exceptional and durham, even in the pouring rain, was charming. it was well worth the 3 hours there and 3 hours back on the train.
thank you, durham, for preserving this amazing unesco world heritage site and welcoming people so graciously and kindly. it's the graciousness and kindness i will most remember. and the lasagna. :)

i wanted compare meal experiences designated quarantine hotels future trips hk friends family.
i staying mira moon. provide choices day meals breakfast, lunch dinner - local asian, international vegetarian. menu choices list 21 days stay sent upon booking, provided link day meal selections. meals must selected days advance fail select, hotel select me. early morning arrival flight selected lunch dinner day. last day quarantine stay, breakfast provided.
dessert provided lunch dinner, choice, daily dessert. idea experience far:
day lunch - stewed chicken red wine sauce, garlic spaghetti, corn bread roll mini croissant, steamed vegetables (carrots, broccoli, cauliflower), mini muffin icing dessert. meal served paper containers, cutlery thin wood disposable. chicken hard solid, somewhat expected bulk food preparation, garlic spaghetti flavourful, good amount vegetables, corn bread roll much corn bread roll slight corn taste, mini croissant good, hard mini muffin could taste sweet icing. main rectangular tray container separate compartments separate different foods keep everything looking nice neat, separate round containers bread dessert. overall, large filling portion size, fairly healthy good amount vegetables, good taste well presented. disposable wood cutlery difficult bend pressed knife took lot effort cut anything fork took multiple stabs pick pieces chicken.
day dinner - viennese fried pork filets fries ketchup tartar sauce, cucumber salad fish roe salad sauce topping, bread roll mini-croissant, dessert kind custard cream topped ground peanuts topping. pork filet pieces quite good, fat lean tough. fries oily. salad good. again, using disposable wood knife cut pork pieces real effort.
column5:
i just started my second hk arrival quarantine. my first was in november 2020 and i was able to pick any hotel and arrange my own meals. this time (march 2021), i am under the designated quarantine hotel scheme with 21 days quarantine and 3 meals provided by the hotel.
i wanted to compare meal experiences at designated quarantine hotels for future trips back to hk for myself and friends and family.
i am staying at mira moon. they provide 3 choices for each day for each of the 3 meals of breakfast, lunch and dinner - local asian, international and vegetarian. the menu choices list for all 21 days of my stay was sent to me upon booking, and i was provided with a link for each day to make my meal selections. meals must be selected 5 days in advance and if i fail to select, the hotel would select for me. i had a very early morning arrival flight so i selected lunch and dinner for the first day. for the last day of the quarantine stay, only breakfast is provided.
dessert is provided with lunch and dinner, but no choice, just the daily dessert. to give you an idea of the experience so far:
day 1 lunch - stewed chicken in red wine sauce, garlic spaghetti, corn bread roll and mini croissant, steamed vegetables (carrots, broccoli, cauliflower), mini muffin with icing dessert. meal served in paper containers, cutlery is thin wood disposable. chicken a bit hard and solid, somewhat expected in bulk food preparation, garlic spaghetti really flavourful, good amount of vegetables, corn bread roll not much like corn bread and more like a roll with a slight corn taste, mini croissant good, hard to say what the mini muffin is as all i could taste was the sweet icing. the main rectangular tray container had 4 separate compartments to separate the different foods and keep everything looking nice and neat, and there were separate round containers for the bread and dessert. overall, large filling portion size, fairly healthy with good amount of vegetables, good taste and well presented. the disposable wood cutlery is difficult to use as they bend when pressed so the knife took a lot of effort to cut anything and the fork took multiple stabs to pick up pieces of chicken.
day 1 dinner - viennese fried pork filets with fries with ketchup and tartar sauce, cucumber salad with fish roe and salad sauce topping, bread roll and mini-croissant, dessert was some kind of custard cream topped with ground up peanuts topping. pork filet pieces were quite good, had some fat so not too lean and tough. fries were not oily. salad good. again, using disposable wood knife to cut the pork pieces was a real effort.

then from matsumoto, i will use one of the discounted bus tickets to get to shirakawago, takayama, kamikochi, and then kanazawa. 
from kanazawa, i'd take a bullet train or high-speed bus to kyoto/osaka. i'd probably stay in osaka instead of kyoto cos the hotels in kyoto are usually more expensive. a couple of days in each city and i'd also extend my trip to cities close to osaka such as himeji and okayama.
himeji castle was ranked the best castle in japan so highly recommended. and don't forget to drop by its garden just next to it cos is beautiful. 
and if you have time, you can also visit mt. shosha in himeji that gives you a great view. 
in okayama, there is okayama castle and its garden korakuen. 
lastly, kurashiki bikan quarter is a great spot to drop by as it is known as the little venice of japan! 
i think the above should fill up your whole month. and hopefully, the info is enough for you to plan. you can always get more info if you leave comments or fill out the contact form :)

column5:
hi, i'm on day #8 of my quarantine, so thought i would provide a little insight.
my asq is maple hotel in bang na. i'm in the basic room, cost is 33k. overall i'm very satisfied with my choice.
room: the room itself is quite spacious for 1 person. i have some workout videos on my laptop and there was just enough space for that. it's a basic room, not elegant, but clean, quiet and functional. there is a medium size fridge that i've made good use of because my gf kindly delivered a large care package of fruit and salads. the ac works fine and is quiet. the room also has a very good workspace and quality chair (this is important to me as some of the other asq's that i considered did not). wifi has been very dependable - there is a router in each room as well as ethernet cable. i did have some issues early on but it turned out to be an issue specific to my room and they promptly sent a technician to resolve it. they also lent me an ethernet adapter as my computer does not have a rj45 port. i was going to order from lazada, so when i asked if that was allowed, they said yes, but also mentioned they could lend me one. so big +1 for helpful service.
food: one thing i found out in doing my dd, is that some asq's do not have their own kitchen and rely on an outside caterer. as a result food choices are very limited (or nil) and there is no choice on timing. maple on the other hand prepares everything in-house and the choices are wide (about 20 choices for lunch/dinner). there is also about a 4 hour time window for each meal and you can request preferred times. so while i would rate the food as just "decent", the fact there is a broad choice and you can specify the time is a big positive. the food was never cold, often luke warm and sometimes piping hot (there are about 4 pasta choices and i think because the containers are filled to the brim, these were always nice and hot). the one negative i would say about the food is lack of vegatables. even off of the vegetarian menu (vegatables and rice for example), the vegatables were fried in oil and not that appealing. most dishes had just a slice of cucumber/tomatoe as garnish. luckily my gf brought me salads, without this i think i might contract scurvy lol.
getting outside: covid test was day 5 and got my negative result around 10:00 am the following day so i was able to leave my room on day 6. officially you are allowed 1 hr outside your room but this is not really enforced. i think the limit is just in place so that the outside areas don't get over-crowded. maple has quite large rooftop areas on each of the 3 towers with a capacity of 16, but there were typically only 3-4 people there at a time, so i think you could spend as much time up there as you like. also they had a different system depending on whether you were from a high risk country (us is in this group for sure and i assume uk). high riskers had black/brown/white wrist bands and others had orange/yellow/green. i believe that the high risk group are not allowed out of their room until after the second covid test.
balcony: this seems to be a big factor in choosing asq's (it was for me). all maple rooms have balconies usuable from day 0. i was wondering if perhaps this was over-rated, but now having been here i have to say having a balcony was a big plus, especially in the days that you are stuck in your room. even though my view was non-existent (i faced the other tower), it was still nice to put my chair out in the morning, brew my lavazza with my french press and sit out there while the temp was still pleasant.
staff: all very friendly, though most interaction is with the line app - both with the hotel and hospital (to report body temperature).
one negative for some people is that maple does not allow deliveries from 7-11. for me this is no big deal, as unlike just about everybody else, i rarely go to 7-11! there is one in my neighbourhood at home - in 20 years i've never gone in lol. i did bring my own snacks, coffee, tea etc and my gf can bring me anything else.
if i were to do it over, i would likely choose maple again. though if i were with my gf or other family members, i'd be inclined to go up a notch, but for a single low maintenace guy, maple is just fine.
cheers
edited: 10:18 pm, january 30, 2021

column5:
think you are approaching this in the wrong way - which is why you can't work out where to stay,
have a look through some trip reports, top things to do in dubai etc (on the main web page) and work out the things you both want to do: ok so we know you want atlantis for a day and a desert safari (that is normally from around 3pm to 9pm). the other use of your days will then decide where you lay your heads at night. no point staying in the marina if you want to mooch around the older parts of town in the souks and spend a day at dubai mall.
if you want to do the desert, you should think about asking your desert company to drop you off at dubai mall for the fountain show and shopping/drinking/coffees - you don't have to go back to your hotel from the camp.
taxis are cheap by uk standards but 30 minutes in a taxi is still 30 minutes in a taxi. metro is a good option as it gives you another view of the city.
i would also be thinking about hitting at.mosphere, neos and the the vault for drinks - the latter two don't have cover charges i believe or a minimum spend.
if you have the time, tell your hubby to get himself into a backstreet barber for a proper wetshave - superb experience and dirt cheap. satwa is my fav spot: there are options all over the place.

column5:
"would chiang mai be a good base for 10 days or is it too long? "
yes and no,, depending on what you want to get out of your vacation.
1st, muay thai gyms exist in practically every city in thailand, and your hotel could arrange muay thai workouts at your hotel if you request it.
no, 10 days is too long for chiang mai and any other single destination in thailand for a first-time visitor to thailand, chiang mai is not centrally-located, and does not offer a well-rounded thailand travel experience.
yes, 10 days is adequate if you want to earn a ph.d. in chiang mai. as michaelb stated above, chiang mai provides a good base for exploring the surrounding cities that he mentioned above, especially exploring chiang rai in the north.
i would combine chiang mai with a beach destination, not because of the interest in beaches or water activities, but because beach destinations offer a more relaxed atmosphere than the urban cities.

column4:
seems misconception covid suddenly going stop.
it isn't.
covid stay concern future "when stops" - concern countries deal it.
te idea next months "return normal" pie sky.
as thailand shown little ability deal major upturn due new variants countries heading 3rd 4th waves - certainly can't see thailand importing huge numbers tourist regions.
as vaccine - protect certain age groups universal panacea, won'y significant effect herd immunity 70% achieved - thailand less 1% full double injections.
after goals achieved world need foster jabs round next year.
thinking return normal next year therefore unlikely. samui relatively lucky far detect growing complacency amongst expats especially, case pride fall?
column5:
there seems to be a misconception that covid is suddenly going to stop.
it isn't.
covid is here to stay and the concern for the future is not "when it stops" - it won't the concern is how will countries deal with it.
te idea that in the next few months things will "return to normal" is pie in the sky.
as yet thailand has shown little ability to deal with a major upturn due to new variants and other countries are heading into 3rd and 4th waves - i certainly can't see thailand importing huge numbers of tourist from those regions.
as for the vaccine - it may protect certain age groups at first but it is not a universal panacea, it won'y have a significant effect until herd immunity at 70% is achieved - and thailand is less than 1% on full double injections.
after these goals have been achieved the world will then need foster jabs all round in the next year.
thinking a return to normal by next year therefore is very unlikely. samui has been relatively lucky so far but one can detect there is a growing complacency amongst expats especially, is this a case of pride before the fall?

column5:
you need to be mindful of covid restrictions, whilst restrictions are easing there still might be restrictions in place when you arrive particularly re nightlife. i believe some clubs are now open but dancing is limited etc...
if sightseeing is a priority then the downtown area is good shout but if nightlife is higher up on your priority list then the marina might suit you better.
july isnâ€™t the best month for sightseeing due to the high humidity and walking long distances isnâ€™t particularly pleasant. the fountains, burj khalifa etc can be done together and if youâ€™re looking for afternoon tea then you could combine this with tea at atmosphere.
as for your nights out, there are many ladies nights on wednesdays which are worth taking advantage of but thursday is going to be your main night out, itâ€™s the start of the weekend and a busy night.
iâ€™d then be inclined to do a brunch on friday but iâ€™d pick this depending on where you plan to stay - after brunch youâ€™ll probably want an earlier night which will suit you as you have to be up early for your onward flight the following day.
personally for such a short visit, iâ€™d forgo the desert safari as theyâ€™re touristy and a bit gimmicky and iâ€™d rather spend my limited time seeing more of dubai

column4:
depends much money want spend see sites. want easy public transport rather jump taxis time slow little.
there fair see abu dhabi emirates and, whilst region open, discount side trip muscat oman (especially 'dubai' early).
i weeks enough time see highlights, couple day trips abu dhabi (the mosque well worth look), beaten track hit beach/pool couple days too.
off beaten track: head satwa see real workers live - lots fun, busy evening - indian/pakistani food, amazing iranian cheese bread cheap haircut, wet shave head massage. change $15 (probably above!)
column5:
it also depends how much money you want to spend to see the sites. if you want to take things easy and use public transport rather jump in taxis all of the time it will slow you down a little.
there is also a fair bit to see in abu dhabi and the other emirates and, whilst you are in the region and if things are open, i wouldn't discount a side trip to muscat in oman (especially if you do 'dubai' early).
i think in 2 weeks you'll have enough time to see the highlights, a couple of day trips to abu dhabi (the mosque is well worth a look), get off the beaten track and hit the beach/pool for a couple of days too.
off the beaten track: head down to satwa to see how the real workers live - its a lots of fun, busy in the evening - great for indian/pakistani food, some amazing iranian cheese bread and a cheap haircut, wet shave and head massage. you'll get change out of $15 (probably for all of the above!)

column4: went greece 1976 husband camped europe four months. iâ€™m sure itâ€™s changed then. left car campground athens took ferry crete, elderly man met ferry persuaded six follow foot home wife ran pensione. stayed three four nights explored island. served amazing meal grape trellis every night. returned athens campground and, young foolish, discovered orthodox easter shops closed. managed find small stall somewhere bought dozen eggs. eggs loaf bread eked days closed stores. iâ€™d love greece weâ€™re ever allowed leave canada again!
column5: i went to greece in 1976 when my husband and i camped around europe for four months. iâ€™m sure itâ€™s changed a bit since then. we left our car at a campground in athens and took the ferry to crete, where an elderly man met the ferry and persuaded about six of us to follow him on foot to his home where he and his wife ran a pensione. we stayed for three or four nights while we explored the island. they served us an amazing meal under the grape trellis every night. we returned to the athens campground and, being young and foolish, we discovered it was orthodox easter when all the shops were closed. we managed to find a small stall somewhere where we bought a dozen eggs. those eggs and a loaf of bread were eked out over the few days of closed stores. iâ€™d love to go back to greece if weâ€™re ever allowed to leave canada again!

column5:
'i am planning on going to edinburgh in may of 2022. we are going to take a day trip to alnwick' since the i became a we within a few words i suspect you'll travel with at least one other person, in which case one of these  may be worth buying, especially if you plan other rail journeys.
at present lner's service in first is reduced, with the offer of a packaged sweet or savoury snack and a hot or cold drink as well as a hot toastie (contents depend on the time of day). lner have resumed trolley service to the passengers at their seats, and they may have returned to the usual multiple offers of drinks and snacks. if their catering supplier hasn't changed the biscuits and cake slices they offer are quite good ... said wishing i could book a rail ticket and look forward to their ginger cake slices.
since you plan to travel next year let's say that services will be back to what they were pre-pandemic. with tickets in first you could visit the lounge at edinburgh waverley for a cup of tea and some biscuits, a nice way to start the trip. the fastest trains to alnmouth take just over an hour which may be too short a trip for a hot meal but perhaps not by that time.
standard would be fine for the trip from waverley station, but if you want to experience first even for a short trip then do so. seating is 2-1 rather than 2-2 with more pitch between rows and perhaps a quieter carriage.
you certainly don't have to decide what to book now as tickets for may next year won't be available for many months.

see games happening extended quarantine testing required athletes officials. refer australian open tennis tournament. due strict quarantine regulations, roger federer playing alone spend weeks away family, family stuck hotel room long stays tournament.
therefore, *if* games on, full athlete participation, sports professionals consider medal icing cake. could allow spectators japanese limited capacity (like npb 2020). international tourists banned.
overall, decision made spring comes. winter wave expected. numbers find way domestically, could see putting brakes on.

column5:
i can see the games happening if an extended quarantine with testing is required for athletes and officials. refer to the australian open tennis tournament. due to the strict quarantine regulations, roger federer won't be playing since either he alone has to spend 5 weeks away from his family, or his family has to be stuck in the hotel room for however long he stays in the tournament.
therefore, *if* the games go on, there might not be full athlete participation, especially in some of the sports where professionals consider a medal just an icing on the cake. they could still allow spectators but japanese only and in limited capacity (like npb did in 2020). international tourists might still be banned.
overall, i think a decision won't be made until the spring comes. the winter wave was always expected. if the numbers don't find a way to go down domestically, then i could see them putting the brakes on.
to a certain extent, i think japan isn't combating the pandemic correctly. quarantine is still not strict. a person i know who is married to a japanese woman recently flew to osaka. he taxied to a pension but he did say he was allowed to leave and buy take-out. any interaction is just not a good idea. they should follow the south korea/new zealand model where folks arriving must be booked into a designated hotel. all meals are to be provided, etc.

column5:
for festivities (parties, drink and dance) and decorations, saigon takes the cake for both christmas and new year's eve.
if you want something more intimate, try Ä‘Ã  láº¡t in the central highlands. it's also cooler so you'll see the locals dressed more to the season. (note that the locals in general do not tolerate the cold as well as westerners.) the daily temperature there is normally 55-70f, but they'll be dressing like it's 40-55f.
another thing to look for is the da lat flower festival. they don't have a fixed period of time for it, but it's between 4 to 7 days.
it may start before christmas, after christmas, or even after new year; you'll just have to check on it.
hanoi has its own christmas flavor, somewhere in between, and it's almost as cool as Ä‘Ã  láº¡t at that time of the year.
if you want to try something different, try either nam Ä‘á»‹nh or thÃ¡i bÃ¬nh province. they have the largest concentration of churches in the country in a smaller area. best to ride a motorbike/pillion for this option since you'd want to check out several small towns and villages on this trip. these provinces are located in the red river delta to the southeast of hÃ  ná»™i so the difference in temperature is usually a few degrees.
cheers,
john

column4:
asq form online list 7-11 items could order dropped outside room day (order noon). mostly snacks (chips, noodle cups, seaweed) drinks (sodas, green teas).
i saw chance exchange money arrival process, pretty much herded airport awaiting asq shuttle. minimized points contact.
column5:
at my asq they had a form online with a list of 7-11 items that you could order and they would be dropped outside your room by 8 pm the same day (order before noon). it was mostly snacks (chips, noodle cups, seaweed) and drinks (sodas, green teas).
i saw no chance to go exchange money during the arrival process, you are pretty much herded through the airport and into your awaiting asq shuttle. they have minimized your points of contact.

column5:

a good coffee is based upon personal preference. i like small one off coffee shops i stay away from the chain coffee shops like amazon and starbucks. there are a few i like. i like black canyon when i am traveling as i know and like the product. every shop uses a different coffee, knowing what coffee they use and how they prepare it . the only thing i drink coffee wize is expresso yen. the coffee shops i like use a pinch of salt in the coffee and sweet milk.

column4:
amazon state owned via ptt. explains prices low many them.
my (thai) wife enjoys fighting staff amazon cafes want charge extra cold milk side put tea - done western world. memory large mug steaming hot tea thb 40, excellent price. sell good coffee too.
column5:
amazon are state owned via ptt. this explains why their prices are low and why there are so many of them.
my (thai) wife enjoys fighting with the staff in amazon cafes because at some they want to charge extra if you ask for cold milk on the side to put in tea - as is done in most of the western world. from memory a large mug of steaming hot tea is just thb 40, an excellent price. they sell good coffee too.

column4:
went oban stopped balloch shores loch lomond fine fish chips chipper main street, ate sitting bench overlooking loch.
you park free past boat trips public toilet self cleaning ones main street.
we stop village gretna green we're going scotland (not service station) walk shops fresh air leg stretch there's cafes coffee ice cream clean toilets well plenty parking. follow signs gretna gateway outlet village.
column5:
when we went to oban we stopped in balloch on the shores of loch lomond and had fine fish and chips from the chipper on the main street, which we ate sitting on a bench overlooking the loch.
you can park free just past where the boat trips go from and there is a public toilet which is one of the self cleaning ones on the main street.
we also always stop in the village of gretna green when we're going to scotland (not the service station) and have a walk around the shops there for some fresh air and a leg stretch and there's a few cafes for a coffee or ice cream and clean toilets as well as plenty parking. follow the signs for gretna gateway outlet village.
